As mark wrote to Dr. Math
On 09/20/2004 at 04:49:33 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>The continuous random variable X has a uniform distribution on 
>0<x<a. Find the cumulative distribution function of X.
>
>Two independent observations X1 and X2 are made of X and the larger 
>of the two values is denoted by L.
>
>(i) use the fact that L<x if and only if both X1<x and X2<x to find 
>the cumulative distribution function of L.
>
>[Difficulty]
>I do not know what to do with L or X1 and X2
>
>[Thoughts]
>i found the cumulative dist function of X to be 
>F(x)= 0      x<0
>      x/a    0<x<a
>      1      x>a

Hi Mark,

Thanks for writing to Doctor Math.

I'll try to get you started. I'll be using lower case l, so don't 
confuse it with 1 (one).

    F(l) = P(L < l)

         = P(X1 < l and X2 < l)

Can you finish it from there? Rember that X1 and X2 are independent. 
Write again if you need more help.

